# ## 🔑 Key Insights
#
# 1. **Total energy potential:** ~4 million kWh/month from road movement alone
# 2. **Homes powered:** ~16,000–17,000 households (0.3% of Ghana's ~6M households)
# 3. **Ashanti Region** outperforms Greater Accra in homes powered due to higher speeds and lower household consumption
# 4. **Trucks** contribute disproportionately to energy potential due to their mass (KE ∝ mass)
# 5. **Road quality matters:** Poor roads reduce effective speed, cutting energy potential by 30–40%
# 6. Even at 25% efficiency, this represents a meaningful supplemental energy source
#
# ## 💡 Implications
# - Piezoelectric roads or regenerative braking systems could turn Ghana's traffic into a distributed power grid
# - Highest impact: Greater Accra, Ashanti, Western (high traffic + urban density)
# - Policy angle: Integrate energy harvesting into road construction (GHA already spends $100M+/year on roads)
